# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: de-architectura
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Hardy wished to justify his life's work in mathematics for two reasons.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Firstly, having survived a heart attack and being at the age of 62, Hardy knew that he was approaching old age and that his mathematical creativity and skills were declining.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] By devoting time to writing the Apology, Hardy was admitting that his own time as a creative mathematician was finished.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] In his foreword to the 1967 edition of the book, C.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Snow describes the Apology as "a passionate lament for creative powers that used to be and that will never come again".
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] In Hardy's words, "Exposition, criticism, appreciation, is work for second-rate minds. [...] It is a melancholy experience for a professional mathematician to find himself writing about mathematics.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Secondly, at the start of World War II, Hardy, a committed pacifist, wanted to justify his belief that mathematics should be pursued for its own sake rather than for the sake of its applications.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] He began writing on this subject when he was invited to contribute an article to *Eureka*, the journal of The Archimedeans (the Cambridge University student mathematical society).
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] One of the topics the editor suggested was "something about mathematics and the war", and the result was the article "Mathematics in war-time".
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Hardy later incorporated this article into *A Mathematician's Apology*.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Hardy wanted to write a book in which he would explain his mathematical philosophy to the next generation of mathematicians.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] He hoped that in this book he could inspire future generations about the importance of mathematics without appealing to its applied uses.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Hardy initially submitted *A Mathematician's Apology* to Cambridge University Press with the intention of personally paying for its printing, but the Press decided to fund publication with an initial run of four thousand copies.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] For the 1940 first edition, Hardy sent postcards to the publisher requesting that presentation copies be sent to his sister Gertrude Emily Hardy (1878–1963), C.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Broad, John Edensor Littlewood, Sir Arthur Eddington, C.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Snow, the cricketer John Lomas (to whom G.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] One of the main themes of the book is the beauty that mathematics possesses, which Hardy compares to painting and poetry.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] For Hardy, the most beautiful mathematics was that which had no practical applications (pure mathematics) and, in particular number theory, Hardy's own field.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Hardy contends that if useful knowledge is defined as knowledge which is likely to contribute to material comfort without respect to mere intellectual satisfaction, then most of higher mathematics is useless.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] He justifies the pursuit of pure mathematics with the argument that its very "uselessness" means that it cannot be misused to cause harm.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] On the other hand, Hardy denigrates much of the applied mathematics as either being "trivial", "ugly", or "dull" and contrasts it with "real mathematics", which is how he describes pure mathematics.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] If an application of number theory were to be found, then certainly no one would try to dethrone the "queen of mathematics" by it.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] What Gauss meant, according to Hardy, is that the underlying concepts that constitute number theory are deeper and more elegant compared to those of any other branch of mathematics.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Another theme is that mathematics is a "young man's game".
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Hardy believed that anyone with a talent for mathematics should develop and use that talent while they are young, before their ability to create original mathematics starts to decline in middle age.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] This view reflects Hardy's increasing depression at the waning of his own mathematical skill.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] For Hardy, real mathematics was essentially a creative activity, rather than an explanatory or expository one.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Hardy's opinions were heavily influenced by the academic culture of the universities of Cambridge and Oxford between World War I and World War II.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Some of Hardy's examples seem unfortunate in retrospect.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] Applicability itself is not the reason that Hardy considered applied mathematics inferior to pure mathematics; it is the simplicity and vulgarity that belong to applied mathematics that led him to describe it as he did.
[src:de-architectura/a-mathematician-s-apology] He considered that Rolle's theorem, for example, cannot be compared to the elegance and preeminence of the mathematics produced by Évariste Galois and other pure mathematicians, although it is of some importance for calculus.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] The main aim of the treatise was to argue that painting was a science.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] The manuscripts were begun in Milan while Leonardo was under the service of Ludovico Sforza (between 1482 and 1499), being worked on substantially for the last 25 years of Leonardo's life.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] The works later published in this collection drew from writing of Leon Battista Alberti and Cennino Cennini.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] Upon Leonardo's death, he left his notebooks to his pupil and heir Francesco Melzi to be published, a task of overwhelming difficulty because of its scope and Leonardo's idiosyncratic writing.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] Sometime before 1542, Melzi gathered together the papers for *A Treatise on Painting* from 18 of Leonardo's "books" (two-thirds of which have gone missing).
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] After Melzi's death in 1570, the collection passed to his son, the lawyer Orazio, who initially took little interest in the journals, but they were later dispersed.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] It was printed in an abridged form in French and Italian as *Trattato della pittura* by Raffaelo du Fresne in 1651.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] After Melzi's version was rediscovered in the Vatican Library, the treatise was first published in its modern form in 1817.
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] In 1937, Max Ernst wrote in *Cahiers d'Art* that Leonardo's advice on the studying of stains on walls caused him an "unbearable visual obsession".
[src:de-architectura/a-treatise-on-painting] All editions of the treatise are kept at the Elmer Belt Library of Vinciana at UCLA.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] The **abbey library of St Gall** (German: *Stiftsbibliothek*) is a significant medieval monastic library located in St.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] In 1983, the library, as well as the Abbey of St Gall, were designated a World Heritage Site, as "an outstanding example of a large Carolingian monastery and was, since the 8th century until its secularisation in 1805, one of the most important cultural centres in Europe".
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] It is one of the oldest monastic libraries in the world.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] The library was founded by Saint Othmar, founder of the Abbey of St.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] During a fire in 937, the Abbey was destroyed, but the library remained intact.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] The library hall, designed by the architect Peter Thumb in a Rococo style, was constructed between 1758 and 1767.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] There is a Greek inscription above the entrance door, ΨΥΧΗΣ ΙΑΤΡΕΙΟΝ (*psukhēs iatreion*).
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] It translates as "healing place for the soul", based on an inscription at the Library of Ramesses II.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] The library collection is the oldest in Switzerland, and one of the earliest and most important monastic libraries in the world.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] The library holds almost 160,000 volumes, with most available for public use.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] In addition to other printed books, the collection includes 1650 *incunabula* (books printed before 1500), and 2100 manuscripts dating back to the 8th through 15th centuries; among the most notable of the latter are items of Irish, Carolingian, and Ottonian production.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] These codices are held inside glass cases, each of which is topped by a carved cherub offering a visual clue as to the contents of the shelves below; for instance, the case of astronomy-related materials bears a cherub observing the books through a telescope.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] Books published before 1900 are to be read in a special reading room.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] The manuscript B of the *Nibelungenlied* is kept here.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] A virtual library has been created to provide broader access to the manuscripts: *Codices Electronici Sangallenses*.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] This project has been expanded to include codices from other libraries as well and is operating under the name e-codices.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] Currently, more than 900 manuscripts from the Abbey library of St Gall are available in digital format.
[src:de-architectura/abbey-library-of-saint-gall] The library is home to the mummy of Shep-en-Isis.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:de-architectura/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:de-architectura/agatharchus] However, as this appears to contradict Aristotle's assertion that scenic painting was introduced by Sophocles, some scholars understand Vitruvius to mean merely that Agatharchus constructed a stage.
[src:de-architectura/agatharchus] It was probably not till towards the end of Aeschylus's career that scenic painting was introduced, and not till the time of Sophocles that it was generally made use of, which may account for what Aristotle says.
[src:de-architectura/agatharchus] Agatharchus was therefore the first painter known to have used graphical perspective on a large scale, although rare occurrences of perspective do appear in vase painting around the middle of the 6th century BC.
[src:de-architectura/agatharchus] He is also said to have led the way for later painters, such as Apollodorus.
[src:de-architectura/agatharchus] Agatharchus was a contemporary of Alcibiades and Zeuxis, and was often singled out for the ease and rapidity with which he finished his works.
[src:de-architectura/agatharchus] Plutarch and Andocides at greater length tell an anecdote of Alcibiades having inveigled Agatharchus to his house and kept him there for more than three months in strict durance, compelling him to paint it.
[src:de-architectura/agatharchus] The speech of Andocides above referred to seems to have been delivered after the destruction of Melos (416 BC) and before the expedition to Sicily (415 BC); so that from the above data the age of Agatharchus may be accurately fixed.
[src:de-architectura/alba-rojo-cama] Rojo was born on 28 April 1961 in Mexico City.
[src:de-architectura/alba-rojo-cama] She was the daughter of artist Vicente Rojo Almazán (1932–2021) and his wife, editor Alba Cama de Rojo (1937–2003), both of whom were originally from Barcelona and became refugees in Mexico from the Spanish Civil War.
[src:de-architectura/alba-rojo-cama] After high school at Colegio Madrid in Mexico City, she studied mathematics at the National Autonomous University of Mexico from 1981 to 1986, and then worked for the university as a science communicator, before devoting herself to sculpture in the late 1980s.
[src:de-architectura/alba-rojo-cama] She died on 16 August 2016 after a three-year battle with cancer.
[src:de-architectura/alba-rojo-cama] as well as a 2016 calendar combining photos of her artworks with mathematical challenges.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Canonized in 1931, he was known during his lifetime as *Doctor universalis* and *Doctor expertus*; late in his life the sobriquet *Magnus* was appended to his name.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Söder have referred to him as the greatest German philosopher and theologian of the Middle Ages.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Catholic Church distinguishes him as one of the Doctors of the Church.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] It seems likely that Albertus Magnus was born sometime before 1200, given well-attested evidence that he was aged over 80 on his death in 1280.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Two later sources say that Albert was about 87 on his death, which has led 1193 to be commonly given as the date of Albert's birth, but this information does not have enough evidence to be confirmed.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert was probably born in Lauingen (now in Bavaria), since he called himself 'Albert of Lauingen', but this might simply be a family name.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Most probably his family was of *ministerial* class; his familial connection with (being son of the count) the Bollstädt noble family is almost certainly mere conjecture by 15th-century hagiographers.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert was probably educated principally at the University of Padua, where he received instruction in Aristotle's writings.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] A late account by Rudolph de Novamagia refers to Albertus' encounter with the Blessed Virgin Mary, who convinced him to enter Holy Orders.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In 1223 (or 1229), he became a member of the Dominican Order, and studied theology at Bologna and elsewhere.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Selected to fill the position of lecturer at Cologne, Germany, where the Dominicans had a house, he taught for several years there, as well as in Regensburg, Freiburg, Strasbourg, and Hildesheim.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] During his first tenure as lecturer at Cologne, Albert wrote his *Summa de bono* after having a discussion with Philip the Chancellor concerning the transcendental properties of being.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In 1245, Albert became master of theology under Guerric of Saint-Quentin, the first German Dominican to achieve this distinction.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Following this turn of events, Albert was able to teach theology at the University of Paris as a full-time professor, holding the seat of the Chair of Theology at the College of St.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] During this time Thomas Aquinas began to study under Albertus.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert was the first to comment on virtually all of the writings of Aristotle, thus making them accessible to wider academic debate.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The study of Aristotle brought him to study and comment on the teachings of Muslim academics, notably Avicenna and Averroes, and this would bring him into the heart of academic debate.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In 1254, Albert was made provincial of the Dominican Order and fulfilled the duties of the office with great care and efficiency.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] During his tenure, he publicly defended the Dominicans against attacks by the secular faculty of the University of Paris, commented on John the Evangelist, and answered what he perceived as errors of the Islamic philosopher Averroes.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] This innovation initiated the tradition of Dominican scholastic philosophy put into practice, for example, in 1265 at the Order's *studium provinciale* at the convent of Santa Sabina in Rome, out of which would develop the Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas, the "Angelicum".
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In 1260, Pope Alexander IV made him bishop of Regensburg, an office from which he resigned after three years.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] During the exercise of his duties he enhanced his reputation for humility by refusing to ride a horse, in accord with the dictates of the Order, instead traversing his huge diocese on foot.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In 1263, Pope Urban IV relieved him of the duties of bishop and asked him to preach the Eighth Crusade in German-speaking countries.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] After this, he was especially known for acting as a mediator between conflicting parties.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In Cologne, he is known not only for being the founder of one of Germany's oldest universities there, but also for "the big verdict" (der Große Schied) of 1258, which brought an end to the conflict between the citizens of Cologne and the archbishop.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Among the last of his labors was the defense of the orthodoxy of his former pupil, Thomas Aquinas, whose death in 1274 grieved Albert (the story that he travelled to Paris in person to defend the teachings of Aquinas can not be confirmed).
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert was a scientist, philosopher, astrologer, theologian, spiritual writer, ecumenist, and diplomat.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Under the auspices of Humbert of Romans, Albert molded the curriculum of studies for all Dominican students, introduced Aristotle to the classroom and probed the work of Neoplatonists, such as Plotinus.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Indeed, it was the thirty years of work done by Aquinas and himself that allowed for the inclusion of Aristotelian study in the curriculum of Dominican schools.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] After suffering declining health in 1278, he died on 15 November 1280 in the Dominican convent in Cologne, Germany.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] His relics are located in a Roman sarcophagus in the crypt of the Dominican St.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] His body was claimed to be incorrupt during an exhumation three years after his death.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] However, a later exhumation in 1483 found that only a skeleton remained.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Saint Stephen's Church in Nijmegen, the Netherlands, also houses a relic.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] He was canonized and proclaimed a Doctor of the Church on 16 December 1931 by Pope Pius XI and the patron saint of natural scientists in 1941.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Among the first biographical sources, there were Heinrich von Herford and Luis of Valladolides and, in modern times, the study by James A.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Weisheipl (1980), who reconstructs the life and works of Albertus Magnus taking into account all previous biographies and places his date of birth around 1200.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert's writings collected in 1899 went to thirty-eight volumes.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] These displayed his prolific habits and encyclopedic knowledge of topics such as logic, theology, botany, geography, astronomy, astrology, mineralogy, alchemy, zoology, physiology, phrenology, justice, law, friendship, and love.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] He digested, interpreted, and systematized the whole of Aristotle's works, gleaned from the Latin translations and notes of the Arabian commentators, in accordance with Church doctrine.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Most modern knowledge of Aristotle was preserved and presented by Albert.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] His principal theological works are a commentary in three volumes on the Books of the Sentences of Peter Lombard (*Magister Sententiarum*), and the *Summa Theologiae* in two volumes.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The latter is in substance a more didactic repetition of the former.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert's activity, however, was more philosophical than theological (see Scholasticism).
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert believed that Aristotle's approach to natural philosophy did not pose any obstacle to the development of a Christian philosophical view of the natural order.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert's knowledge of natural science was considerable and for the age remarkably accurate.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] His industry in every department was great: not only did he produce commentaries and paraphrases of the entire Aristotelian corpus, including his scientific works, but Albert also added to and improved upon them.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] His books on topics like botany, zoology, and minerals included information from ancient sources, but also results of his own empirical investigations.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] These investigations pushed several of the special sciences forward, beyond the reliance on classical texts.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In the case of embryology, for example, it has been claimed that little of value was written after Aristotle until Albert, who managed to identify organs within eggs.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Furthermore, Albert also effectively invented entire special sciences, where Aristotle has not covered a topic.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] For example, prior to Albert, there was no systematic study of minerals.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Much of Albert's empirical contributions to the natural sciences have been superseded, but his general approach to science may be surprisingly modern.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] For example, in *De Mineralibus* (Book II, Tractate ii, Ch.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In the centuries since his death, many stories arose about Albert as an alchemist and magician.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] For example, in his commentary, *De mineralibus*, he refers to the power of stones, but does not elaborate on what these powers might be.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] A wide range of Pseudo-Albertine works dealing with alchemy exist, though, showing the belief developed in the generations following Albert's death that he had mastered alchemy, one of the fundamental sciences of the Middle Ages.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] These include *Metals and Materials*; the *Secrets of Chemistry*; the *Origin of Metals*; the *Origins of Compounds*, and a *Concordance*which is a collection of *Observations on the philosopher's stone*; and other alchemy-chemistry topics, collected under the name of *Theatrum Chemicum*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] He is credited with the discovery of the element arsenic and experimented with photosensitive chemicals, including silver nitrate.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] He did believe that stones had occult properties, as he related in his work *De mineralibus*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] However, there is scant evidence that he personally performed alchemical experiments.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] According to legend, Albert is said to have discovered the philosopher's stone and passed it on to his pupil Thomas Aquinas, shortly before his death.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert does not confirm he discovered the stone in his writings, but he did record that he witnessed the creation of gold by "transmutation." Given that Thomas Aquinas died six years before Albert's death, this legend as stated is unlikely.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert was deeply interested in astrology, as has been articulated by scholars such as Paola Zambelli and Scott Hendrix.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Throughout the Middle Ages—and well into the early modern period—astrology was widely accepted by scientists and intellectuals who held the view that life on earth is effectively a microcosm within the macrocosm (the latter being the cosmos itself).
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] It was believed that correspondence therefore exists between the two and thus the celestial bodies follow patterns and cycles analogous to those on earth.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] With this worldview, it seemed reasonable to assert that astrology could be used to predict the probable future of a human being.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert argued that an understanding of the celestial influences affecting us could help us to live our lives more in accord with Christian precepts.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The most comprehensive statement of his astrological beliefs is to be found in two separate works that he authored around 1260, known as the *Speculum astronomiae* and *De Fato*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] However, details of these beliefs can be found in almost everything he wrote, from his early *De natura boni* to his last work, the *Summa theologiae*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] His *speculum* was critiqued by Gerard of Silteo.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert considered the tides to be influenced by the moon.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Based on ancient Greek theories of light and Abu Ma'shar al-Balkhi's astrological explanations, he proposed a mixed theory where the Moon doubly attracts the water by its intrinsic astrological humid nature and by the heat that the moonlight produces.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert believed that all natural things were compositions of matter and form, to which he referred as *quod est* and *quo est*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert also believed that God alone is the absolute ruling entity.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert's version of hylomorphism is very similar to the Aristotelian doctrine.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert is known for his commentary on the musical practice of his times.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Most of his written musical observations are found in his commentary on Aristotle's *Poetics*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] He rejected the idea of "music of the spheres" as ridiculous: movement of astronomical bodies, he supposed, is incapable of generating sound.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] He wrote extensively on proportions in music, and on the three different subjective levels on which plainchant could work on the human soul: purging of the impure; illumination leading to contemplation; and nourishing perfection through contemplation.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Of particular interest to 20th-century music theorists is the attention he paid to silence as an integral part of music.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Both of his early treatises, *De natura boni* and *De bono*, start with a metaphysical investigation into the concepts of the good in general and the physical good.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert refers to the physical good as *bonum naturae*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert does this before directly dealing with the moral concepts of metaphysics.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In Albert's later works, he says in order to understand human or moral goodness, the individual must first recognize what it means to be good and do good deeds.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] This procedure reflects Albert's preoccupations with neo-Platonic theories of good as well as the doctrines of Pseudo-Dionysius.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert's view was highly valued by the Catholic Church and his peers.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert devoted the last tractatus of *De Bono* to a theory of justice and natural law.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert places God as the pinnacle of justice and natural law.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] God legislates and divine authority is supreme.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Before his time, there had been no work specifically devoted to natural law written by a theologian or philosopher.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert mentions friendship in his work, *De bono*, as well as presenting his ideals and morals of friendship in the very beginning of *Tractatus II*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Later in his life he published *Super Ethica*.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] With his development of friendship throughout his work it is evident that friendship ideals and morals took relevance as his life went on.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert comments on Aristotle's view of friendship with a quote from Cicero, who writes, "friendship is nothing other than the harmony between things divine and human, with goodwill and love".
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert agrees with this commentary but he also adds in harmony or agreement.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert calls this harmony, *consensio*, itself a certain kind of movement within the human spirit.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert fully agrees with Aristotle in the sense that friendship is a virtue.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert relates the inherent metaphysical contentedness between friendship and moral goodness.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert describes several levels of goodness; the useful (*utile*), the pleasurable (*delectabile*) and the authentic or unqualified good (*honestum*).
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The iconography of the tympanum and archivolts of the late 13th-century portal of Strasbourg Cathedral was inspired by Albert's writings.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert is frequently mentioned by Dante, who made his doctrine of free will the basis of his ethical system.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In his *Divine Comedy*, Dante places Albertus with his pupil Thomas Aquinas among the great lovers of wisdom (*Spiriti Sapienti*) in the Heaven of the Sun.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In Mary Shelley's *Frankenstein*, the titular scientist, Victor Frankenstein, studies the works of Albertus Magnus.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Pastor Johann Eduard Erdmann considered Albert greater and more original than his pupil Aquinas.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] A number of mostly Catholic schools have been named after Albert, including Albertus Magnus High School in Bardonia, New York; Albertus Magnus Lyceum in River Forest, Illinois; and Albertus Magnus College in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albertus Magnus Science Hall at Thomas Aquinas College, in Santa Paula, California, is named in honor of Albert.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The main science buildings at Providence College and Aquinas College in Grand Rapids, Michigan, are also named after him.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The central square at the campus of the University of Cologne features a statue of Albert and is named after him.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Made by Gerhard Marcks around 1950s, this statue is one of four replicas found in different places around the world (along with University of Jena, University of the Andes, and University of Houston).
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert the Great Chapel and Catholic Student Center is a Roman Catholic campus ministry located in Hammond, Louisiana, serving students of Southeastern Louisiana University.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Academy for Science and Design in New Hampshire honored Albert by naming one of its four houses Magnus House.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] As a tribute to the scholar's contributions to the law, the University of Houston Law Center displays a statue of Albert.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] It is located on the campus of the University of Houston.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Albertus-Magnus-Gymnasium is found in Rottweil, Germany.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In Managua, Nicaragua, the Albertus Magnus International Institute, a business and economic development research center, was founded in 2004.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] In the Philippines, the Albertus Magnus Building at the University of Santo Tomas that houses the Conservatory of Music, College of Tourism and Hospitality Management, College of Education, and UST Education High School is named in his honor.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Saint Albert the Great Science Academy in San Carlos City, Pangasinan, which offers preschool, elementary and high school education, takes pride in having St.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Its main building was named Albertus Magnus Hall in 2008.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] San Alberto Magno Academy in Tubao, La Union is also dedicated in his honor.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] This century-old Catholic high school continues to live on its vision-mission up to this day, offering Senior High school courses.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Due to his contributions to natural philosophy, the bacterium *Agrobacterium albertimagni*, the plant species *Alberta magna*, the crustacean *Bodigiella albertimagni*, the fossil brachiopod *Albasphe albertimagni*, and the asteroid 20006 Albertus Magnus were named after him.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Numerous Catholic elementary and secondary schools are named for him, including schools in Toronto; Calgary; Cologne; and Dayton, Ohio.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Albertus typeface is named after him.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] At the University of Notre Dame du Lac in Notre Dame, Indiana, the Zahm Hall Chapel is dedicated to St.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] John Zahm, C.S.C., after whom the men's residence hall is named, looked to St.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Albert's example of using religion to illumine scientific discovery.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Zahm's work with the Bible and evolution is sometimes seen as a continuation of St.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The second largest student's fraternity of the Netherlands, located in the city of Groningen, is named Albertus Magnus, in honor of the saint.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Vosloorus Catholic parish (located in Vosloorus Extension One, Ekurhuleni, Gauteng, South Africa) is named after the saint.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] The Catholic parish in Leopoldshafen, near Karlsruhe in Germany is also named after him, too, since Albert is the patron saint of scientists and the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology has a large research center nearby.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Since the death of King Albert I, the King's Feast is celebrated in Belgium on Albert's feast day.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Edinburgh's Catholic Chaplaincy which serves the city's universities, is named after St Albert.
[src:de-architectura/albertus-magnus] Sant'Alberto Magno is a titular church in Rome.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] It contains a variety of information on Greek and Roman buildings, as well as prescriptions for the planning and design of military camps, cities, and structures both large (aqueducts, buildings, baths, harbours) and small (machines, measuring devices, instruments).
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] From references to them in the text, it is known that there were at least a few illustrations in original copies (perhaps eight or ten), but perhaps only one of these survived in any medieval manuscript copy.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] This deficiency was remedied in 16th-century printed editions, which became illustrated with many large plates.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Copies were made during the Carolingian Renaissance, but little use was made of them until the 15th century, when the work became of great interest and influence, initially in Italy and then in the rest of Europe.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Probably written between 30 and 20 BC, it combines the knowledge and views of many antique writers, Greek and Roman, on architecture, the arts, natural history and building technology.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius cites many authorities throughout the text, often praising Greek architects for their development of temple building and the orders (Doric, Ionic and Corinthian), and providing key accounts of the origins of building in the primitive hut.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The Roman author gives advice on the qualifications of an architect (Book I) and on types of architectural drawing.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Though often cited for his famous "triad" of characteristics associated with architecture – **utilitas, firmitas and venustas** (utility, strength and beauty) – the aesthetic principles that influenced later treatise writers were outlined in Book III.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Derived partially from Latin rhetoric (through Cicero and Varro), Vitruvian terms for order, arrangement, proportion, and fitness for intended purposes have guided architects for centuries, and continue to do so.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Roman architects were skilled in engineering, art, and craftsmanship combined.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius was very much of this type, a fact reflected in *De architectura*.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He covered a wide variety of subjects he saw as touching on architecture.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] This included many aspects that may seem irrelevant to modern eyes, ranging from mathematics to astronomy, meteorology, and medicine.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] In the Roman conception, architecture needed to take into account everything touching on the physical and intellectual life of man and his surroundings.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius, thus, deals with many theoretical issues concerning architecture.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] For instance, in Book II of *De architectura*, he advises architects working with bricks to familiarise themselves with pre-Socratic theories of matter so as to understand how their materials will behave.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Book IX relates the abstract geometry of Plato to the everyday work of the surveyor.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Astrology is cited for its insights into the organisation of human life, while astronomy is required for the understanding of sundials.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Likewise, Vitruvius cites Ctesibius of Alexandria and Archimedes for their inventions, Aristoxenus (Aristotle's apprentice) for music, Agatharchus for theatre, and Varro for architecture.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius sought to address the ethos of architecture, declaring that quality depends on the social relevance of the artist's work, not on the form or workmanship of the work itself.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Perhaps the most famous declaration from *De architectura* is one still quoted by architects: "Well building hath three conditions: firmness, commodity, and delight".
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] This quote is taken from Sir Henry Wotton's version of 1624, and accurately translates the passage in the work, (I.iii.2) but English has changed since then, especially in regard to the word "commodity", and the tag may be misunderstood.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius also studied human proportions (Book III) and this part of his *canones* were later adopted and adapted in the famous drawing *Homo Vitruvianus* ("Vitruvian Man") by Leonardo da Vinci.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] While Vitruvius is fulsome in his descriptions of religious buildings, infrastructure and machinery, he gives a mixed message on domestic architecture.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Similar to Aristotle, Vitruvius offers admiration for householders who built their own homes without the involvement of an architect.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] His ambivalence on domestic architecture is most clearly read in the opening paragraph of the Introduction to Book 6.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Books VIII, IX, and X of *De architectura* form the basis of much of what is known about Roman technology, now augmented by archaeological studies of extant remains, such as the Pont du Gard in southern France.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Numerous such massive structures occur across the former empire, a testament to the power of Roman engineering.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius's description of Roman aqueduct construction is short, but mentions key details especially for the way they were surveyed, and the careful choice of materials needed.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] His book would have been of assistance to Frontinus, a general who was appointed in the late 1st century AD to administer the many aqueducts of Rome.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Frontinus wrote *De aquaeductu*, the definitive treatise on 1st-century Roman aqueducts, and discovered a discrepancy between the intake and supply of water caused by illegal pipes inserted into the channels to divert the water.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The Roman Empire went far in exploiting water power, as the set of no fewer than 16 water mills at Barbegal in France demonstrates.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The mills ground grain in a very efficient operation, and many other mills are now known, such as the much later Hierapolis sawmill.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius described many different construction materials used for a wide variety of different structures, as well as such details as stucco painting.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Cement, concrete, and lime received in-depth descriptions, the longevity of many Roman structures being mute testimony to their skill in building materials and design.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He advised that lead should not be used to conduct drinking water, clay pipes being preferred.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He comes to this conclusion in Book VIII of *De architectura* after empirical observation of the apparent laborer illnesses in the *plumbum* (lead pipe) foundries of his time.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] However, much of the water used by Rome and many other cities was very hard, minerals soon coated the inner surfaces of the pipes, so lead poisoning was reduced.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius related the famous story about Archimedes and his detection of adulterated gold in a royal crown.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] When Archimedes realized the volume of the crown could be measured exactly by the displacement created in a bath of water, he ran into the street with the cry of "Eureka!", and the discovery enabled him to compare the density of the crown with pure gold.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He showed the crown had been alloyed with silver, and the king was defrauded.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius described the construction of the Archimedes' screw in Chapter 10, although did not mention Archimedes by name.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] It was a device widely used for raising water to irrigate fields and dewater mines.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Other lifting machines mentioned in *De architectura* include the endless chain of buckets and the reverse overshot water-wheel.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Remains of the water wheels used for lifting water have been discovered in old mines such as those at Rio Tinto in Spain and Dolaucothi in west Wales.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] One of the wheels from Rio Tinto is now in the British Museum, and one from the latter in the National Museum of Wales.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The remains were discovered when these mines were reopened in modern mining attempts.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] They would have been used in a vertical sequence, with 16 such mills capable of raising water at least 96 feet (29 m) above the water table.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Each wheel would have been worked by a miner treading the device at the top of the wheel, by using cleats on the outer edge.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] That they were using such devices in mines clearly implies that they were entirely capable of using them as water wheels to develop power for a range of activities, not just for grinding wheat, but also probably for sawing timber, crushing ores, fulling, and so on.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Ctesibius is credited with the invention of the force pump, which Vitruvius described as being built from bronze with valves to allow a head of water to be formed above the machine.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The device is also described by Hero of Alexandria in his *Pneumatica*.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The machine is operated by hand in moving a lever up and down.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He mentioned its use for supplying fountains above a reservoir, although a more mundane use might be as a simple fire engine.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] One was found at Calleva Atrebatum (Roman Silchester) in England, and another is on display at the British Museum.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Their functions are not described, but they are both made in bronze, just as Vitruvius specified.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius also mentioned the several automatons Ctesibius invented, and intended for amusement and pleasure rather than serving a useful function.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius outlined the many innovations made in building design to improve the living conditions of the inhabitants.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Foremost among them is the development of the hypocaust, a type of central heating where hot air developed by a fire was channelled under the floor and inside the walls of public baths and villas.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He gave explicit instructions on how to design such buildings so fuel efficiency is maximized; for example, the *caldarium* is next to the *tepidarium* followed by the *frigidarium*.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He also advised using a type of regulator to control the heat in the hot rooms, a bronze disc set into the roof under a circular aperture, which could be raised or lowered by a pulley to adjust the ventilation.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Although he did not suggest it himself, his dewatering devices such as the reverse overshot water-wheel likely were used in the larger baths to lift water to header tanks at the top of the larger *thermae*, such as the Baths of Diocletian and the Baths of Caracalla.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] That Vitruvius must have been well practised in surveying is shown by his descriptions of surveying instruments, especially the water level or *chorobates*, which he compared favourably with the *groma*, a device using plumb lines.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] They were essential in all building operations, but especially in aqueduct construction, where a uniform gradient was important to provision of a regular supply of water without damage to the walls of the channel.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He described the *hodometer*, in essence a device for automatically measuring distances along roads, a machine essential for developing accurate itineraries, such as the Peutinger Table.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] In Book IV Chapter 1 Subsection 4 of *De architectura* is a description of 13 Athenian cities in Asia Minor, "the land of Caria", in present-day Turkey.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] These cities are given as: Ephesus, Miletus, Myus, Priene, Samos, Teos, Colophon, Chius, Erythrae, Phocaea, Clazomenae, Lebedos, Mytilene, and later a 14th, Smyrnaeans.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Myus, the third city, is described as being "long ago engulfed by the water, and its sacred rites and suffrage".
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] This sentence indicates, at the time of Vitruvius's writing, it was known that sea-level change and/or land subsidence occurred.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The layout of these cities is in general from south to north so that it appears that where Myrus should be located is inland.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] If this is the case, then since the writing of *De architectura*, the region has experienced either soil rebound or a sea-level fall.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Though not indicative of sea-level change, or speculation of such, during the later-empire many Roman ports suffered from what contemporary writers described as 'silting'.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The constant need to dredge ports became a heavy burden on the treasury and some have speculated that this expense significantly contributed to the eventual collapse of the empire.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Roman salt works in Essex, England, today are located at the five-metre contour, implying this was the coastline.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] These observations only indicate the extent of silting and soil rebound affecting coastline change since the writing of *De architectura*.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius's work is one of many examples of Latin texts that owe their survival to the palace *scriptorium* of Charlemagne in the early 9th century.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] This activity of finding and recopying classical manuscripts is part of what is called the Carolingian Renaissance.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The London Vitruvius (British Library, Harley 2767), the oldest surviving manuscript, includes only one of the original illustrations, a rather crudely drawn octagonal wind rose in the margin.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] This was written in Germany in about 800 to 825, probably at the abbey of Saint Pantaleon, Cologne, and has been shown to be one of the most important manuscripts for the further transmission of the text.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] These texts were not just copied, but also known at the court of Charlemagne, since his historian, bishop Einhard, asked the visiting English churchman Alcuin for explanations of some technical terms.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] In addition, a number of individuals are known to have read the text or have been indirectly influenced by it, including: Vussin, Hrabanus Maurus, Hermann of Reichenau, Hugo of St.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Vitruvius's work was "rediscovered" in 1416 by the Florentine humanist Poggio Bracciolini, who found it in the Abbey library of Saint Gall, Switzerland.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] He publicized the manuscript to a receptive audience of Renaissance thinkers, just as interest in the classical cultural and scientific heritage was reviving.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The first printed edition (*editio princeps*), an *incunabulum* version, was published by the Veronese scholar Fra Giovanni Sulpitius in 1486 (with a second edition in 1495 or 1496), but none were illustrated.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The Dominican friar Fra Giovanni Giocondo produced the first version illustrated with woodcuts in Venice in 1511.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] It had a thorough philosophical approach and superb illustrations.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Translations into Italian were in circulation by the 1520s, the first in print being the translation with new illustrations by Cesare Cesariano, a Milanese friend of the architect Bramante, printed in Como in 1521.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] It was rapidly translated into other European languages – the first French version was published in 1547 – and the first German version followed in 1548.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The first Spanish translation was published in 1582 by Miguel de Urrea and Juan Gracian.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The most authoritative and influential edition was publicized in French in 1673 by Claude Perrault, commissioned by Jean-Baptiste Colbert in 1664.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] John Shute had drawn on the text as early as 1563 for his book *The First and Chief Grounds of Architecture*.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Sir Henry Wotton's 1624 work *The Elements of Architecture* amounts to a heavily influenced adaptation, while a 1692 translation was much abridged.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] English-speakers had to wait until 1771 for a full translation of the first five volumes and 1791 for the entire work.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Thanks to the art of printing, Vitruvius's work had become a popular subject of hermeneutics, with highly detailed and interpretive illustrations, and became widely dispersed.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Of the many later editions, the 1914 *Ten Books on Architecture* translated by Morris H.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Late Professor of Classical Philology in Harvard University, is fully available at *Project Gutenberg*, and from the Internet Archive.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The rediscovery of Vitruvius's work had a profound influence on architects of the Renaissance, prompting the rebirth of Classical architecture in subsequent centuries.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Renaissance architects, such as Niccoli, Brunelleschi and Leon Battista Alberti, found in *De architectura* their rationale for raising their branch of knowledge to a scientific discipline as well as emphasising the skills of the artisan.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] One of Leonardo da Vinci's best known drawings, the *Vitruvian Man*, is based on the principles of body proportions developed by Vitruvius in the first chapter of Book III, *On Symmetry: In Temples And In The Human Body*.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The English architect Inigo Jones and the Frenchman Salomon de Caus were among the first to re-evaluate and implement those disciplines that Vitruvius considered a necessary element of architecture: arts and sciences based upon number and proportion.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The 16th-century architect Palladio considered Vitruvius his master and guide, and made some drawings based on his work before conceiving his own architectural precepts.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The earliest evidence of use of the stereographic projection in a machine is in *De architectura*, which describes an anaphoric clock (it is presumed, a *clepsydra* or water clock) in Alexandria.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The clock had a rotating field of stars behind a wire frame indicating the hours of the day.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] The wire framework (the spider) and the star locations were constructed using the stereographic projection.
[src:de-architectura/de-architectura] Similar constructions dated from the 1st to 3rd centuries have been found in Salzburg and northeastern France, so such mechanisms were, it is presumed, fairly widespread among Romans.
